Every Brand in Every Land


The Honickman Empire


"Every Brand in Every Land"
Billion Dollar Beverage Business. Likes to control brands and markets.
We started to distribute our apple juice in little brown beer bottles
through Canada Dry in Phila. in 1983. We signed the contract in March,
but they won't start distribution until after July, so I lost the entire
Spring and Summer. They wouldn't even take over the service of the 500
accounts I had selling my juice in the Philadelphia area.
The contract they drafted gave them the product rights in NY, Baltimore,
Washington and Virginia. But those operations didn't know anything about
it and couldn't give me a decision about whether they would take it on
and start selling it.
I eventually parted with the Baltimore-Washington (after Dick Wolf told
me I would be dead meat)  and NY operations because they could care
less. They wanted to tie up the product and keep me from going elsewhere.
Now this was about the same time Snapple was getting started with their
tea and we made fruit teas also.First told me he couldn't sell my tea because
he had Tetley. But, then took on Snapple Teas in 1990.
They lied about they'll being interested in Snapple and then one day
when I went over there to pick up some samples, I found Snapple everywhere. 
We had 16 oz bottles of fruit drinks-fruit punch, lemonade, grapeade, but
Canada Dry wouldn't take that size and proceeded to killed off my lemonade
by selling the 12 oz bottle almost for the same price as the 16 oz Snapple
Lemonade.
In 1990, Told me my juice cocktails were not the same as Snapple Fruit
Ades, but then after Snapple came out with Juice Cocktails (5% juice) in
1991, told me those were different.
At his companies 25th anniversary celebration, he whispered in my
ear-
"If I didn't take Snapple, someone
else would ...
this way we can control it".
A 600 pound gorilla and his pointy tooth lawyer believe they can make
up the rules as they go along.
The Snapple people had already pulled Snapple from my Maryland distributors
(who sued them and won) because they wanted them to drop my brand. 
We backed off from Canada Dry the first year with them selling Snapple
Teas, lemonade and fruit punch. We found that the Canada Dry salespeople
were selling Snapple and not Elliott's. They killed off my lemonade by
selling the 12 oz lemonade for the same as the Snapple 16 oz instead of
selling my 16 oz lemonade. Then the second year, Snapple came out with
products labeled "Fruit Juice Cocktails"  Canada Dry's spin was these
were different that Elliott's Juice Cocktails. The juice content was lower.
They weren't the same quality...yadda yadda.  We gave them an ultimatum
to sell our fruit juices and fruit drinks exclusively and we eventually
set up a distribution company to sell our products and other products not
yet being distributed in the Philadelphia area.
They said they were going to "split" the sales force with some people
selling Snapple and something else and another group selling Elliott's
and something else. "We have too many brands for one person to sell. This
never happened. I put together a business plan to start up another beverage
distribution plan and had a PERT chart with all the details. I met with
his son, Jeffrey and while impressed told me they were not going to do
that..now.  So in October 1991, we set about to set up shop with a
start up date of April 1992. This was an operation to cover the eight county
Philadelphia metro area with only 10 trucks vs 60+ that Canada Dry had
and 10 salespeople vs 25+ that Canada Dry had. We seemed to have the support
of Imbesi, the Seven-Up operation also located in Conshohocken because
they didn't like the Honickman Empire although they had one of their own.
So the enemy of my enemy is my friend and they agreed to rent up trucks
before our 10 leased trucks were built and delivered.
One day while I was waiting for the phones to be installed, Harold and
Jeffrey came to visit and told me I was making a mistake becoming a
competitor.  In May, the Teamsters were stopping our drivers around
the corner from the warehouse  to organize the drivers and warehouse
personnel. So we had a National Labor Relational Board Election and had
to deal with organized labor and the dance required to treat some people
different than others. I don't think there was much of a out of pocket
cost difference with the union drivers since we had been paying them the
same as other beverage companies. In retrospect, I should have shifted
to a independent owner operator driver sales operation, but my beverage
experts-all from traditional pre-sell soda  operations-led me down
the path of pre-sell salespeople, company cars, next day deliveries requiring
a night shift to pick orders and load trucks and brain dead supervisors
with company cars who hide all day and they came back to ask salespeople
how many cases they sold. Like we had a complete state-of -the-art software
system they gave me that information after the orders were downloaded through
modems and processed.  Five months into the business, we discovered
James
Waldron, my national sales manager who had been the sales manager at
Canada Dry had his own business going and we cleaned house and retrenched
although at the bottling plant was closed by the
bankruptcy trustee and I had that problem to deal with at the same time.
Canada Dry replaced my brand with a knock off of my product line, Country
Pure,  which I stumbled across while attending a "Novell" seminar
in Center City.  and convinced he other Canada Dry buddies to drop
my brand. Then Mott's came out with juices and he dropped Country Pure.
 Country Pure resurrects
it's ugly face in January '03 and guess who is going to distribute it at
low predatory pricing? You got it!
During year two, when we started to distribute Frank's soda which had
been in Philadelphia for over 50 years, he told Super Fresh, a large supermarket
chain, they didn't need another generic soda since they already have their
own brand (which he bottles for them). Of course he now owns the Frank's
brand which has been beaten up to a pulp by Day's Soda. But at least no
one else could sell Frank's.
Under pressure from Corestates, we reluctantly sold our distribution
company to BEI in 1994 at the same time Canada Dry started distributing
Nantucket
Nectars. BEI  was abandoning the 3000 up and down the street accounts
we had and focusing on supermarkets after acquiring Imbesi 7 Up a year
later.  Waldron  was working for for Everfresh and was busy setting
up a distributor network at the same time as "revenge"..
BEI finally folded and the company that had started
"Hank's Root Beer"  had sold their rights to Nantucket Nectars to
Canada Dry. The same company had Arizona tea and this brand went to BEI
and then to Canada Dry although they had Snapple, Mistic and Tetley tea.
So L&M who owned Hank's got out of the distribution business and left
me high and dry without any distribution in Philadelphia. L&M also
owned the rights to a hot beer, Yuengling, and guess who they sold those
rights to? You got it Origlio, who is the Coors distributor owned by Honickman.
In 1991, we were also bottling our juices at Beverage Capital, a plant
owned by Honickman as well as two other plants. We decided to fund a new
dedicated hot fill bottling line at the Maryland
plant, and had a contract to bottle Lipton tea, which Honickman, as
the Pepsi distributor was going to distribute in New Jersey and New York
City).  When the plant was experiencing trouble, instead of offering
to help his buddies at Pepsi get Lipton up and running, he convinced Lipton
to pull out of the new plant to go down the road to his bottling plant
in Baltimore. Without this key piece of business and the revenue, there
was no future for the bottling plant and no way they would be able to reorganize.
It was the major reason why the plant was closed by the bankruptcy trustee.
Hoover's
On line
Here's an interesting law
suit filed against Honickman.
And here's how
Honickman got A&W Root Beer in new York
Here's how Honickman got the rights to 7-Up in
Brooklyn, Queens and Westchester
UNITED STATES COURT OF APPEALS   FOR THE SECOND
CIRCUIT
No. 549, 711 August Term, 1993  Argued: February
11, 1994 Decided: May , 1994
Docket
Nos. 93-7368, 93-7444
Harold Screws Over the 125 Independent Canada Dry Distributors in
NYC.
Plaintiffs-appellants are independent distributors of
soft drink products bottled and/or
distributed by defendant-appellee, Canada Dry Bottling
Company of New York, Inc. ("Canada
Dry"). 1 On November 21, 1990, they sued Canada Dry and
others in the United States
District Court for the Eastern District of New York,
alleging, inter alia, that Canada Dry had
conspired to restrain the trade of soft drink products
in violation of the Sherman Act, the
Clayton Act, the Taft-Hartley Act, and the Racketeer
Influenced and Corrupt Organization Act.
FTC's own report on the soft drink industry. 
Recently made the Forbes List of the 400
Richest People in America


My advice: Always marry a rich girl and have her dad buy you a company.
Harold Honickman owns the Pepsi franchise  in NYC and  half
of New Jersey. He'd like to buy Pepsi Philadelphia, but those FTC lawyers
wouldn't like that...he'd have to sell off Canada Dry, but Cadbury is also
buying out their independent distributors in some markets and Honickman
owns those brands from NY though Virginia.
If he sold everything, his son,  Jeffrey, Baron of Bubbles, wouldn't
have anything to do except count all the family money.
 

Nominated in 2002 to the "Beverage Hall of Fame", Harold is disappointed
he's not the only one and offers money to have it renamed the "Honickman
Beverage Hall of Fame".
You'd think he's a warm compassionate human being now that he's donating
money to various institutions for "naming rights". You can't take it with
you and you might as well be remembered for something besides being a monopolistic
megalomaniac.
 

If I give you money, will you name the moon after me? After all it
doesn't have a name yet!
 

If I give you some money, can you put my statute on top of City Hall
instead of William Penn?

Hark!  Harold must have gotten another beverage brand.
 

Hey! Stop picking on Harold. Just because we're monopolists doesn't
mean we don't have a heart. We just keep it in a jar by the side
of our bed.
 
 
 
 


